2000000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">16. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The Company is currently subject to an audit by U.S. Customs &amp; Border Protection (&#x201C;CBP&#x201D;) in respect of the period from 2006 to 2010. In October 2013, CBP issued the final audit report. In that report CBP projects that unpaid duties totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$12.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million are due for the period under review and recommends collection of the duties due. Crocs responded that these projections are erroneous and provided arguments that demonstrate the amount due in connection with this matter is considerably less than the projection. Additionally, on December 12, 2014, Crocs made an offer to settle CBP&#x2019;s potential claims and tendered </font><font style="display: inline;">$3.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million. At this time, it is not possible to determine how long it will take CBP to evaluate the offer or to predict whether the offer will be accepted. Likewise, if a settlement cannot be reached, it is not possible to predict with any certainty whether CBP will seek to assert a claim for penalties in addition to any unpaid duties, but such an assertion is a possibility.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Mexico&#x2019;s Federal Tax Authority (&#x201C;SAT&#x201D;) has audited the Company&#x2019;s records regarding imports and exports during the period from January 2006 to July 2011. There were two phases to the audit, the first for capital equipment and finished goods and the second for raw materials. The first phase was completed and no major discrepancies were noted by the SAT. On January 9, 2013, Crocs received a notice for the second phase in which the SAT issued a tax assessment (taxes and penalties) of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;">280.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million pesos (approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$22.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million) based on the value of all of Crocs&#x2019; imported raw materials during the audit period. Crocs believes that the proposed penalty amount is unfounded and without merit. With the help of local counsel Crocs filed an appeal by the deadline of March 15, 2013. Crocs has argued that the amount due in connection with the matter, if any, is substantially less than that proposed by the SAT. In connection with the appeal, the SAT required Crocs to post an appeal surety bond in the amount of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;">321.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million pesos (approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$26.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million), which amount reflects estimated additional penalties and interest if the Company is not successful on its appeal. On November 27, 2014, the Superior Chamber of the Federal Tax Court ruled in favor of Crocs and annulled the tax assessment and the corresponding penalty. The SAT filed its appeal of the decision in Crocs&#x2019; favor on February 25, 2015. On June 24, 2015, the Circuit Court rejected SAT&#xB4;s appeal, and thus, confirmed the favorable decision issued to Crocs by the Federal Tax Court. </font><font style="display: inline;">On August 6, 2015, the Circuit Court entered its final written order in favor of Crocs and this matter is now considered closed and the bond commitment has been released. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Crocs is currently subject to an audit by the Brazilian Federal Tax Authorities related to imports of footwear from China between 2010 and 2014. On January 13, 2015</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> Crocs was notified about the issuance of assessments totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$3.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million for the period January 2010 through May 2011. Crocs has disputed these assessments and asserted defenses to the claims</font><font style="display: inline;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">On February 25, 2015</font><font style="display: inline;">,</font><font style="display: inline;"> Crocs received additional assessments totaling approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$8.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million related to the remainder of the audit period. Crocs has also disputed these assessments and asserted defenses to these claims</font><font style="display: inline;">, which also included requesting an interpretation from the trade authorities of whether certain Crocs&#x2019; footwear models are included in the scope of the application of anti-dumping duties on footwear from China</font><font style="display: inline;">. It is anticipated that this matter will take up to several years to be resolved. It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On August 8, 2014, a purported class action lawsuit was filed in California State Court against a Crocs subsidiary, Crocs Retail, LLC (Zaydenberg v. Crocs Retail, LLC, Case No. BC554214). The lawsuit alleged various employment law violations related to overtime, meal and break periods, minimum wage, timely payment of wages, wage statements, payroll records and business expenses. Crocs filed an answer on February 6, 2015, denying the allegations and asserting several defenses. On June 3, 2015, a second purported class action lawsuit was filed in California State Court against Crocs Retail, LLC (Christopher S. Duree and Richard Morely v. Crocs, Inc., Case No. BC583875), making substantially the same allegations as in the Zaydenberg lawsuit. The parties attended a mediation </font><font style="display: inline;">on June 26, 2015, and reached a </font><font style="display: inline;">settlement for </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, which will release the claims in </font><font style="display: inline;">both lawsuits. </font><font style="display: inline;">On September 4, 2015, the Court granted preliminary approval of the settlement and set the final approval hearing for December 14, 2015. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;"> 30, 2015, Crocs estimates that the ultimate resolution of these litigation matters and other disputes could result in a loss that is </font><font style="display: inline;">reasonably possible between </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">6.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million in aggregate, of which </font><font style="display: inline;">$5.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> has been accrued</font><font style="display: inline;"> and is reported in the balance sheet in line &#x2018;Accrued expenses and other liabilities&#x2019;</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Although Crocs is subject to other litigation from time to time in the ordinary course of business, including employment, intellectual property and product liability claims, Crocs is not party to any other pending legal proceedings that Crocs believes would reasonably have a material adverse impact on its business, financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> Certain leases contain rent escalation clauses (step rents) that require additional rental amounts in the later years of the term. Rent expense for leases with step rents or rent holidays is recognized on a straight-line basis over the lease term beginning on the lease inception date. Deferred rent is included in the condensed consolidated balance sheets in &#x2018;Accrued expenses and other current liabilities.&#x2019;</font> </p> <p condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) for interim financial information Estimates and assumptions are used in accounting for, among other things, the valuation of acquisition-related assets and liabilities, allowances for uncollectable accounts, taxes and related valuation allowances, loss contingencies, fair value measurements, impairment assessments, useful lives of long-lived assets and share-based compensation. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 15000000 475323000 146801000 443891000 153267000 4700000 1600000 4500000 1400000 1400000 500000 1400000 400000 3075000 3531000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">9. REVOLVING CREDIT FACILITY &amp; BANK BORROWINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Senior </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On September 25, 2009, Crocs entered into a Revolving Credit and Security Agreement (</font><font style="display: inline;">as amended, </font><font style="display: inline;">the &#x201C;Credit Agreement&#x201D;) with the lenders named therein and PNC Bank, National Association ("PNC"), as a lender and administrative agent for the lenders. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On April 2, 2015, Crocs entered into the Sixth Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (the &#x201C;Sixth Amendment&#x201D;) pursuant to which certain terms of the Credit Agreement were amended. The Sixth Amendment primarily amended certain definitions of the financial covenants to be more favorable to Crocs including (i) setting the minimum fixed charge coverage ratio to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through December 31, 2015, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.15</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through March 31, 2016 and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.25</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 for each quarte</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">r thereafter, (ii)&nbsp;setting the leverage r</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">atio to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">4.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through March 31, 2016 and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">3.75</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 for each quarter thereafter and&nbsp;(iii) reducing the Company&#x2019;s global cash requirement from </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$100</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$50</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On September 1, 2015, the Company entered into the Eighth Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (the &#x201C;Eighth Amendment&#x201D;) pursuant to which certain terms of the Credit Agreement were amended. The Eighth Amendment primarily amended certain definitions of the financial covenants to become more favorable to the Company including (i) increasing the exclusion of ca</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">sh and non-cash char</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ges from the EBITDAR calculation to up to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$85.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, not to exceed </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$65.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million with respect to cash charges, (ii) setting the minimum fixed charge coverage ratio to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.95</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 for the period ended September 30, 2015, (iii) allowing up to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$40.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million in stock repurchases to be made during the quarter ended September 30, 2015, (iv) suspending stock repurchases if the fixed charge coverage ratio is less than </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00, and (v) eliminating the administrative agent basket through December 31, 2015.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The Credit Agreement enables Crocs to borrow up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$100.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, with the ability to increase commitments to </font><font style="display: inline;">$125.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million subject to certain conditions, and is currently set to mature in </font><font style="display: inline;">December 2017</font><font style="display: inline;">. The Credit Agreement is available for working capital, capital expenditures, permitted acquisitions, reimbursement of drawings under letters of credit, and permitted dividends, distributions, purchases, redemptions and retirements of equity interests. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement are secured by all of the Company&#x2019;s assets including all receivables, equipment, general intangibles, inventory, investment property, subsidiary stock and intellectual property. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement bear interest at a variable rate. For domestic rate loans, the interest rate is equal to the highest of (i) the daily federal funds open rate as quoted by ICAP North America, Inc. plus </font><font style="display: inline;">0.5%</font><font style="display: inline;">, (ii) PNC's prime rate and (iii) a daily LIBOR rate plus </font><font style="display: inline;">1.0%</font><font style="display: inline;">, in each case there is an additional margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">0.25%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">1.00%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. For LIBOR rate loans, the interest rate is equal to a LIBOR rate plus a margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">1.25%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">2.00%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. The Credit Agreement requires monthly interest payments with respect to domestic rate loans and at the end of each interest period with respect to LIBOR rate loans. The Credit Agreement further provides for a limit on the issuance of letters of credit to a maximum of </font><font style="display: inline;">$20.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million. The Credit Agreement contains provisions requiring Crocs to maintain compliance with certain restrictive and financial covenants. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, the Company had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under the Credit Agreement. As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, the Company had outstanding letters of credit of $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, which were reserved against the borrowing base under the terms of the Credit Agreement. As of September 30, 2015, the Company was not in compliance with the fixed charge coverage ratio and </font><font style="display: inline;">the </font><font style="display: inline;">leverage ratio under the Credit Agreement. On November 3, 2015, the Company entered into the Ninth Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Agreement pursuant to which the Company received a waiver from the lenders of the financial covenant violations as of September 30, 2015 and the Credit Agreement was amended to </font><font style="display: inline;">allow for up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$15</font><font style="display: inline;">.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million in stock repurchases</font><font style="display: inline;"> in the fourth quarter of 2015.</font><font style="display: inline;"> The Company anticipates it will be in compliance with its covenants as of December 31, 2015, however, there can be no assurance that the Company will be in compliance at that date. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Asia Pacific Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On August 28, 2015, a Crocs subsidiary entered into a revolving credit facility agreement with HSBC Bank (China) Company Limited, Shanghai Branch (&#x201C;HSBC&#x201D;) as the lender. The revolving credit facility enables Crocs to borrow uncommitted dual currency revolving loan facilities up to RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">40.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, or the USD equivalent, and import facilities up to RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">60.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, or the USD equivalent, however, the total combined facility amount may not exceed an aggregate facility limit of RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">60.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million. This revolving credit facility</font><font style="display: inline;"> supports possible future net working capital needs in China. For loans denominated in USD, the interest rate is </font><font style="display: inline;">2.1%</font><font style="display: inline;"> per annum plus LIBOR for three months or any other period as may be determined by HSBC at the end of each interest period. For loans denominated in RMB, interest equals the one year benchmark lending rate effective on the loan drawdown date set forth by the People&#x2019;s Bank of China with a </font><font style="display: inline;">10%</font><font style="display: inline;"> mark-up and is payable on the maturity date of the related loan. </font><font style="display: inline;">The revolving credit facility is guaranteed by Crocs, Inc. </font><font style="display: inline;">and certain accounts receivables in China are pledged as security under the revolving credit facility. </font><font style="display: inline;">The revolving credit facility contains provisions requiring Crocs to maintain compliance with certain restrictive covenants and as of September 30, 2015, Crocs was in compliance with all relevant covenants. As of September 30, 2015, Crocs had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under the revolving credit facility.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Long-Term Bank Borrowings</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On December 10, 2012, Crocs entered into a Master Installment Payment Agreement (&#x201C;Master IPA&#x201D;) with PNC in which PNC financed the Company&#x2019;s recent implementation of a new enterprise resource planning (&#x201C;ERP&#x201D;) system, which began in October 2012 and was substantially completed in early 2015. The terms of each note payable, under the Master IPA, consist of a fixed interest rate and payment terms based on the amount borrowed and the timing of activity throughout the </font><font style="display: inline;">implementation of the ERP system. The Master IPA is subject to cross-default, cross-termination, and is co-terminous with the Credit Agreement. As</font><font style="display: inline;"> discussed above, as of</font><font style="display: inline;"> September 30, 2015, the Company was </font><font style="display: inline;">not in compliance with </font><font style="display: inline;">the fixed charge coverage </font><font style="display: inline;">ratio and the leverage ratio under the Credit Agreement. On November 3, 2015, t</font><font style="display: inline;">he Company received a waiver from the lenders </font><font style="display: inline;">of the financial covenant violations as of September 30, 2015.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">The Company anticipates it will be in compliance with its covenants as of December 31, 2015.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, Crocs had </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">7.7 million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$11.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively, of debt outstanding under </font><font style="display: inline;">five</font><font style="display: inline;"> separate notes payable, </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">of which </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$5.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">4 million and $5.3 million, respectively, </font><font style="display: inline;">represents current installments. As of September 30, 2015, the notes bear interest rates ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.45%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.79%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">and maturities ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">September 2016</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">September 2017</font><font style="display: inline;">. As this debt arrangement relates solely to the construction and implementation of an ERP system for use by the entity, interest expense was capitalized to the condensed consolidated balance sheets until the assets were placed into service on January 1, 2015. During the three and nine months ended September 30, 2015, </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> interest was capitalized. During the three and nine months ended September 30, 2014, Crocs capitalized </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, in interest expense related to this debt arrangement. Interest rates and payment terms are subject to change as further financing occurs under the Master IPA.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: 9pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt;font-size:9pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-family:Times New Roman;;"> (1)</font> </p> </td><td 30, 2015 for all borrowings outstanding pursuant to each debt instrument, including any applicable margin. The interest rates presented represent stated rates and do not include the impact of the derivative instruments, deferred financing costs, original issue premiums or discounts and commitment fees, all of which affect our overall cost of borrowing</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:9pt;color:#000000;">.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Depreciation</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: During the nine months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs </font><font style="display: inline;">recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$13.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">$18.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, in depreciation expense of </font><font style="display: inline;">which </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> for both periods</font><font style="display: inline;"> was recorded in &#x2018;Cost of sales,&#x2019; with the remaining amounts recorded in &#x2018;Selling, general and administrative expenses&#x2019; on the condensed consolidated statements of operations. As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, accumulated depreciation was </font><font style="display: inline;">$106.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$99.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 319639000 7913000 3005000 5376000 134755000 17230000 814000 3356000 44533000 14590000 13180000 917000 743000 1838000 1918000 61887000 3229000 4355000 245918000 5935000 1910000 1237000 16902000 20372000 676000 5144000 96015000 11795000 9823000 560000 781000 2552000 62325000 3410000 6481000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">8. DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Crocs transacts business in various foreign countries and is therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In general, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Crocs </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">enters</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> into foreign currency exchange forward contracts and currency swap derivative instruments to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreign currency exchange rates. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> these derivative instruments</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> do not qualify</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as hedging instruments under the accounting standar</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ds for derivatives and hedging, they </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value recognized in &#x2018;Foreign currency transaction </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">loss</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, net&#x2019; in the condensed consolidated statements of operations. For purposes of the cash flow statement, Crocs classifies the cash flows </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">from derivative instruments </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged items, generally within &#x2018;Cash provided by </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">(used in) </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">operating activities.&#x2019; </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign currency exchange contracts as of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below are denominated in their U.S. Dollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily represent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of the Company&#x2019;s exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;"> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: STOCK</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">-BASED COMPENSATION</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Stock-based compensation expense is based on the grant date fair value and is recognized on a straight-line basis over the applicable vesting period. During the three months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, of pre-tax stock-based inline;">$0.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively,</font><font style="display: inline;"> is included in cost of sales on the condensed consolidated statements of operations. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font nine months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$8.9</font><font As of September 30, 2015, the unvested RSUs are expected to be amortized over the remaining weighted average period of </font><font style="display: inline;">1.93</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;years, which consists of a remaining weighted average </font><font style="display: inline;">period of </font><font style="display: inline;">1.99</font><font style="display: inline;"> years related to performance-based awards and a remaining weighted average period of </font><font style="display: inline;">1.85</font><font style="display: inline;"> years related to time-based awards.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Appointment of Interim CFO</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">On September&nbsp;7, 2015, Jeffrey J. Lasher resigned as Senior Vice President - Finance and Chief Financial Officer of Crocs. His resignation was effective October&nbsp;1, 2015 and he will remain employed to provide transition services to the Company through November&nbsp;7, 2015. On September&nbsp;7, 2015, the Company appointed Mike Smith as Interim Chief Financial Officer, effective October&nbsp;1, 2015. </font><font style="display: inline;">In connection with his appointment as Interim Chief Financial Officer, </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Mr.&nbsp;Smith was granted a </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">RSU</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> award representing the right to receive </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">10,000</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock. The RSUs will vest in </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">three</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> equal annual installments beginning on the first anniversary of the grant date, subject to Mr.&nbsp;Smith&#x2019;s continued employment with the Company through each vesting date</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">. &nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Appointment of CFO</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On November 4, 2015, the board of directors </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of the Company (the &#x201C;Board&#x201D;) </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">appointed Carrie Teffner as Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer, effective December 16, 2015. In connection with her appointment, Ms. Teffner will resign as a member of the Board prior to her start date with the Company. She will serve as the Company&#x2019;s principal financial officer and principal accounting officer. Mike Smith</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> will no longer serve as Interim Chief Financial Officer on her start date.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Upon the commencement of her employment, Ms. Teffner will be granted a time-vesting RSU award representing the right to receive shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock equal to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$1,000,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, based on a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">-day weighted-average stock price as of the date Ms. Teffner&#x2019;s appointment was publicly announced. The RSUs will vest in </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> annual installments beginning on the first anniversary of her start date, subject to her continued employment with the Company as of each vesting date.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In addition, Ms. Teffner will be granted a performance-vesting RSU award, representing the right to receive shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock equal to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$1,000,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, based on a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">-day weighted-average stock price as of the date Ms. Teffner&#x2019;s appointment was publicly announced. The RSU will vest based on the achievement of certain share price levels on or before the fourth anniversary of her start date, subject to continued employment with the Company.&nbsp; </font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 3067000 3067000 3000000 0.38 0.12 -0.32 -0.37 0.37 0.12 -0.32 -0.37 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. The Company&#x2019;s Series A convertible preferred stock (&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;) issued in 2014 represents participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of the Company&#x2019;s non-vested restricted stock and restricted stock unit awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in the Company&#x2019;s earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security</font><font style="display: inline;">, if any,</font><font style="display: inline;"> is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above. This method assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note 12&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 12pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:12pt;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">12. EARNINGS PER SHARE</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table illustrates the basic and diluted EPS computations for the three and nine months ended September</font><font style="display: inline;"> 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2015 and 2014:</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;"> <tr> <td valign="bottom" style="width:33.64%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:01.88%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Diluted EPS is calculated using the two-class method for options and RSUs and the if-converted method for series A preferred stock. Approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">2.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">0.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million options and RSUs, for the three months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;"> 30, 2015 and 2014, respectively, and approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">2.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">1.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million options and RSUs for the nine months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;"> 30, 2015 and 2014 were excluded in the calculation of diluted EPS under the two-class method because the effect would be anti-dilutive. The Series A preferred shares were excluded in the calculation of diluted EPS under the if-converted method because the effect would be anti-dilutive. If converted, Series A preferred stock would represent </font><font style="display: inline;">approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">15.8%</font><font style="display: inline;"> of the Company&#x2019;s common stock outstanding or </font><font style="display: inline;">13.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million additional common shares, as of </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;"> 30, 2015. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note 13 &#x2013; Series A Preferred Stock for f</font><font style="display: inline;">urther details regarding the preferred share offering.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Stock Repurchase Plan Authorizations</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Crocs continues to evaluate options to maximize the returns on its cash and maintain an appropriate capital structure, including, among other alternatives, repurchases of common stock. On December 26, 2013, Crocs&#x2019; board of directors (the &#x201C;Board&#x201D;) approved the repurchase of up to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$350.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million of the Company&#x2019;s common stock. The number, price, structure and timing of the repurchases will be at the Company&#x2019;s sole discretion and future repurchases will be evaluated by the Company depending on market conditions, liquidity needs and other factors. Share repurchases may be made in the open market or in privately negotiated transactions. The repurchase authorization does not have an expira</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">tion date and does not obligate</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Crocs to acquire any particular amount of its common stock. The Board may suspend, modify or terminate the repurchase program at any time without prior notice.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the three months ended September 30, 2015, Crocs repurchased approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">2.3</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million shares at a weighted average price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$14.50</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> per share for an aggregate price of approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$33.1</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> excluding related commission charges</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> under the publicly-announced repurchase plan. During the nine months ended September 30, 2015, Crocs repurchased approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">5.6</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million shares at a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">weighted average price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$13.64</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> per share for an aggregate price of approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$75.8</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> excluding related commission charges</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> under the publicly-announced repurchase plan. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the three months ended September 30, 2014, Crocs repurchased approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">2.9</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million shares at a weighted average price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$14.74</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> for an aggregate price of approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$43.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, excluding related commission charges, under the publicly-announced repurchase plan. -176000 -6305000 23824000 19008000 100000 0 P2Y8M5D P1Y11M27D P1Y10M6D P1Y11M5D 800000 7600000 9700000 200000 17300000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">7. FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENTS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">GAAP provides for a fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to the valuation techniques used to measure fair value into three broad levels. Level 1 inputs are quoted market prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities that the reporting entity has the ability to access at the measurement date. Level 2 inputs are inputs other than quoted market prices included within Level 1 that are observable for the asset or liability, either directly or indirectly. Level 3 inputs are unobservable inputs for the asset or liability.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, our assets subject to fair value measurements consisted solely of cash equivalents of </font><font style="display: inline;">$15.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$23.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, which are Level 1 assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Non-Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority of the Company&#x2019;s non-financial instruments, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is required to be evaluated for impairment and the carrying value is not recoverable, the carrying value would be adjusted to the lower of its cost or fair value and an impairment charge would be recorded. During the three months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">5.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and $2.6 million, respectively, in impairment charges associated with the Company&#x2019;s retail locations. During the nine months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">7.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and $5.8 million, respectively, in impairment charges associated with the Company&#x2019;s retail locations</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 78126000 4170000 4931000 62591000 5798000 636000 95587000 4170000 5054000 81406000 4846000 111000 19175000 5451000 12524000 14449000 16901000 18620000 175130000 4170000 6702000 157615000 5945000 698000 182707000 4170000 6674000 166774000 4846000 243000 97004000 1771000 95024000 147000 62000 87120000 1620000 85368000 132000 -4278000 -1290000 -2631000 -2908000 9019000 99000 -2711000 2497000 -6963000 -2620000 2044000 2030000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">4.
