6381000 2350000 5288000 5383000 11669000 7733000 4774000 1614000 1337000 0.0263 6700000 0 83527000 -87885000 -44829000 -11796000 -5295000 6940000 48168000 15767000 -13023000 -24024000 37905000 12009000 -24065000 -27776000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Debt Issuance Costs</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In April 2015, the Financial Accounting Standards Board ("FASB") issued Accounting Standards Update ("ASU") 2015-03: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs,</font><font style="display: inline;"> which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be </font><font style="display: inline;">presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, </font><font style="display: inline;">consistent with debt discounts. </font><font style="display: inline;">ASU 2015-03 requires retrospective adoption and will be effective for Crocs beginning in the first quarter of 2016. Early adoption is permitted. Crocs does not expect this pronouncement will have a material impact on the condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Share-Based Payments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">I</font><font style="display: inline;">n June 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity&#x2019;s satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2015. The Company is currently </font><font style="display: inline;">evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; </font><font style="display: inline;">ASU 2014-09 </font><font style="display: inline;">becomes effective for</font><font style="display: inline;"> reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2017. Early application is permitted for reporting periods (including interim</font><font style="display: inline;"> periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. </font><font style="display: inline;">This new standard permits the use of either the retrospective or cumulative effect transition method. </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on the condensed consolidated financial statements.</font><font style="display: inline;"> Crocs has not yet selected a transition method or determined the effect of the standard on financial reporting once the standard is effective. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Inventory</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-11: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory</font><font style="display: inline;">, which modifies existing requirements regarding measuring inventory at the lower of cost or market. </font><font style="display: inline;">Specifically, t</font><font style="display: inline;">his </font><font style="display: inline;">standard </font><font style="display: inline;">eliminates the need to determine and consider replacement cost or </font><font style="display: inline;">net realizable value</font><font style="display: inline;"> less an approximately normal profit margin when measuring inventory. This standard is effective prospectively beginning January 1, 2017, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently </font><font style="display: inline;">evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Other new pronouncements issued but not effective until after September 30, 2015 are not expected to have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 4 3 59846000 -13750000 45000 -104537000 178088000 53451000 95383000 29254000 1113000 -5405000 15000 -31755000 38258000 15094000 13475000 9689000 -6743000 -18843000 -113736000 125836000 48884000 58775000 18177000 -20730000 -6549000 -29927000 15746000 11734000 178000 3834000 14635000 4952000 12171000 4166000 82307000 26629000 73181000 23323000 96206000 31320000 85176000 27431000 736000 261000 176000 58000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;;"> 1.</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <a name="_24e68ca378c9475f89fe3e1123342a7a"></a><a name="_52e23e3419b7420da8eda0a5fae61467"></a><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;">ORGANIZATION &amp; BASIS OF PRESENTATION</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Organization</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Crocs,&nbsp;Inc. and its subsidiaries (collectively the &#x201C;Company,&#x201D; </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#x201C;Crocs,&#x201D; </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#x201C;we,&#x201D; &#x201C;our&#x201D; or &#x201C;us&#x201D;) are engaged in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing and distribution of footwear, apparel and accessories for men, women and children.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Basis of Presentation</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) for interim financial information and with the rules&nbsp;and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;) for reporting on Form&nbsp;10-Q. Accordingly, these financial statements do not include all information required for complete financial statements. In the opinion of management, these condensed consolidated financial statements reflect all adjustments (consisting solely of normal recurring matters) considered necessary for a fair statement of the results for the interim periods presented. The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements and these notes thereto should be read in conjunction with </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">. The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The preparation of financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reporting amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expense during the reporting period. Estimates and assumptions are used in accounting for, among other things, the valuation of acquisition-related assets and liabilities, allowances for uncollectable accounts, taxes and related valuation allowances, loss contingencies, fair value measurements, impairment assessments, useful lives of long-lived assets and share-based compensation. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Debt Issuance Costs</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In April 2015, the Financial Accounting Standards Board ("FASB") issued Accounting Standards Update ("ASU") 2015-03: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs,</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">consistent with debt discounts. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ASU 2015-03 requires retrospective adoption and will be effective for Crocs beginning in the first quarter of 2016. Early adoption is permitted. Crocs does not expect this pronouncement will have a material impact on the condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Share-Based Payments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">I</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">n June 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity&#x2019;s satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2015. The Company is currently </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ASU 2014-09 </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">becomes effective for</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2017. Early application is permitted for reporting periods (including interim</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">This new standard permits the use of either the retrospective or cumulative effect transition method. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Crocs is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on the condensed consolidated financial statements.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> Crocs has not yet selected a transition method or determined the effect of the standard on financial reporting once the standard is effective. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Inventory</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-11: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, which modifies existing requirements regarding measuring inventory at the lower of cost or market. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Specifically, t</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">his </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">standard </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">eliminates the need to determine and consider replacement cost or </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">net realizable value</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> less an approximately normal profit margin when measuring inventory. This standard is effective prospectively beginning January 1, 2017, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Other new pronouncements issued but not effective until after September 30, 2015 are not expected to have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 2201000 3878000 25968000 23587000 19650000 18891000 29306000 11739000 97337000 87420000 12277000 12430000 170000 -416000 388000 217000 -6000 405000 4484000 1776000 588000 5000 5229000 1684000 90093000 75928000 9656000 3088000 338000 6230000 75000 94000 5166000 8900000 787000 261000 29457000 7572000 13891000 4235000 8233000 3067000 8833000 3000000 0.001 0.001 4000000 4000000 0 0 30156000 29782000 1300000 1255000 182220000 174000 68288000 50188000 9129000 25258000 202300000 147200000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">6. RESTRUCTURING ACTIVITIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restructuring</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On July 21, 2014, Crocs announced strategic plans for long-term improvement and growth of the business. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">These plans comprise four key initiatives including (1) streamlining the global product and marketing portfolio, (2) reducing direct investment in smaller geographic markets, (3) creating a more efficient organizational structure by reducing excess overhead and enhancing the decision making process, and (4) closing or converting retail locations around the world. The initial effects of these plans were incurred in 2014 and are continuing throughout 2015. Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> recorded restructuring charges of $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">million and $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">7.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million during the three and nine month periods ended September 30, 2015, respectively</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During 2015, Crocs currently estimates restructuring costs related to store closures and changes in organizational structure of approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$8.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$12.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, but the Company can make no assurance that actu</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">al costs will not differ.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Retail Store Closings</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">As mentioned above, the Company plans to close additional retail locations around the globe. As such, Crocs expects to incur certain exit costs specific to store closures including operating lease termination costs, rent obligations for leased facilities, net of expected sublease income, and other expenses in association with this plan. During the three and nine month periods ended September 30, 2015, Crocs </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">closed </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">2</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">18</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> company</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">-operated retail locations that</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> were identified in the initial </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">restructuring plan</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">, respectively. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">These locations were selected for closure by management based on historical and projected profitability levels, relocation plans, and other factors. As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, Crocs had a liability of approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">2.7</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">$4.9</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> million, respectively, related to locations to be closed and other reductions in workforce in accrued restructuring on the condensed consolidated balance sheets. The calculation of accrued store closing reserves primarily includes future minimum lease payments from the date of closure to the end of the remaining lease term, net of contractual or estimated sublease income. Crocs records the liability at fair value in the period the store is closed</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> valign="bottom" style="width:02.04%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:12.75pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-align:right;" nowrap="nowrap"><div style="float:left"></div>1,422,409&nbsp; </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:02.04%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none hidden;font-size:0pt;"> &nbsp;</p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:02.04%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none style="width:12.78%;border-top:1pt solid #000000 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:2pt double #000000 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:12.75pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size:10pt;text-align:right;" nowrap="nowrap"><div style="float:left"></div>13.64&nbsp; </td> </tr> </table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">15. OPERATING SEGMENTS AND GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During 2014, Crocs had </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">four</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> reportable operating segments based on the geographic nature of the Company&#x2019;s operations: Americas, Asia Pacific, Japan and Europe. Crocs&#x2019; &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; category aggregates insignificant operating segments that do not meet the reportable segment threshold and includes manufacturing operations located in Mexico,&nbsp;Italy and Asia. The composition of the Company&#x2019;s reportable operating segments is consistent with that used by Crocs&#x2019; chief operating decision maker, (&#x201C;CODM&#x201D;) to evaluate performance and allocate resources.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Subsequent to December 31, 2014, Crocs&#x2019; internal reports reviewed by the CODM began consolidating Japan into the Asia Pacific segment. This change aligned the Company&#x2019;s internal reporting to its new strategic model and management structure, as Japan and Asia Pacific are now managed and analyzed as one operating segment by management and the CODM. Accordingly, Crocs now has </font><font style="display: inline;">three</font><font style="display: inline;"> reportable segments for 2015 as well as the &#x201C;Other Businesses&#x201D; category and prior period segment results have been reclassified to reflect this change.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Each of the reportable operating segments derives its revenues from the sale of footwear, apparel and accessories to external customers as well as intersegment sales. Revenues of the &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; category are primarily made up of intersegment sales. The remaining revenues for &#x201C;Other businesses&#x201D; represent non-footwear product sales to external customers. Intersegment sales are not included in the measurement of segment operating income or regularly reviewed by the CODM and are eliminated when deriving total consolidated revenues.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Segment performance is evaluated based on segment results without allocating corporate expenses, or indirect general, administrative and other expenses. Segment profits or losses include adjustments to eliminate intersegment sales. As such, reconciling items for segment operating income represent unallocated corporate and other expenses as well as intersegment eliminations. The CODM evaluates the performance of Crocs&#x2019; segments based on gross margin and direct operating profit excluding unallocated amounts. The CODM is not regularly provided information on segment assets, nor is such information considered when evaluating the performance of the segments. Additionally, there was no material change in the amounts or methodology of assets allocated to segments, other than the inclusion of assets allocated to the Japan segment now included in the Asia Pacific segment. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following tables set forth information related to Crocs&#x2019; reportable operating business segments as of and for the three and nine months ended September 30, 2015 and 2</font><font style="display: inline;">014:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div align="left"></hr> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" 10473000 8886000 P8M9D 909901 190035 14.78 12.76 15987 2644126 100650 10000 15.01 10.35 14.74 7488 1997471 15987 3387553 11991 3268668 15.61 15.78 15.01 11.20 15.01 11.18 11484 463028 3996 29500 style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">2. SUMMARY OF SIGNIFICANT ACCOUNTING POLICIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. The Company&#x2019;s Series A convertible preferred stock (&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;) issued in 2014 represents participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of the Company&#x2019;s non-vested restricted stock and restricted stock unit awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in the Company&#x2019;s earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security</font><font style="display: inline;">, if any,</font><font style="display: inline;"> is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above. This method assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note 12&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Asset Impairments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Crocs periodically evaluates all of its long-lived assets for impairment when events or circumstances would indicate the carrying value of a long-lived asset may not be fully recoverable. </font><font style="display: inline;">The following table summarizes retail asset impairment charges by reportable operating segment for the three and nine months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014 related to certain </table></div> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Depreciation</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">During the three months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$4.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$6.4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, in depreciation expense of </font><font style="display: inline;">which </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.5</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, was recorded in &#x2018;Cost of sales,&#x2019; with the remaining amounts recorded in &#x2018;Selling, general and administrative expenses&#x2019; on the condensed consolidated statements of operations. During the nine months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs </font><font style="display: inline;">recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$13.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">$18.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, in depreciation expense of </font><font style="display: inline;">which </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> for both periods</font><font style="display: inline;"> was recorded in &#x2018;Cost of sales,&#x2019; with the remaining amounts recorded in &#x2018;Selling, general and administrative expenses&#x2019; on the condensed consolidated statements of operations. As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, accumulated depreciation was </font><font style="display: inline;">$106.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$99.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Accounts Receivable </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Accounts receivable represent amounts due from customers. Accounts receivable are recorded at invoiced amounts, net of reserves and allowances, and do not bear interest. We use our best estimate to determine the required allowance for doubtful accounts based on a variety of factors including the length of time receivables are past due, economic trends and conditions affecting our customer base and historical collection experience. Specific provisions are recorded for individual receivables when we become aware of a customer's inability to meet its financial obligations. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In the third quarter of 2015, we had multiple China distributors default on their payment obligations. As a result, we reassessed the collectability of our accounts receivable balances for our China operations, and we concluded a significant increase in our allowance for doubtful accounts was required. Accordingly, we have increased our China allowance for doubtful accounts by an additional </font><font style="display: inline;">$18.9</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, resulting in total allowances in China of </font><font style="display: inline;">$40.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$21.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million as of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our net accounts receivable balance for our China operations as of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014 is </font><font style="display: inline;">$4.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$18.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively.&nbsp; </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The changes in the allowance for doubtful accounts, inclusive of unapplied rebate reserves, and reserves for sale returns and allowances for the three months ended September 30, 2015, and 2014, are as follows:</font> Carrying value represents the weighted average interest rate in effect at September 30, 2015 for all borrowings outstanding pursuant to each debt instrument, including any applicable margin. The interest rates presented represent stated rates and do not include the impact of the derivative instruments, deferred financing costs, original issue premiums or discounts and commitment fees, all of which affect our overall cost of borrowing Includes a corporate component consisting primarily of corporate support and administrative functions, costs associated with share-based compensation, research and development, brand marketing, legal, restructuring, depreciation and amortization of corporate and other assets not allocated to operating segments. Includes $2.9 million and $2.5 million of accumulated amortization of software held under a capital lease as of September 30, 2015, and December 31, 2014, respectively, and is amortized using the straight-line method over the useful life. Includes $4.1 million of software held under a capital lease classified as capitalized software as of both September 30, 2015, and December 31, 2014. Change in goodwill and indefinite lived intangible assets relate entirely to foreign currency translation. Unused borrowing capacity represents the maximum available under the applicable facility at September 30, 2015 without regard to covenant compliance calculations or other conditions precedent to borrowing. Minimum rentals include all lease payments as well as fixed and variable common area maintenance, parking and storage fees, which were approximately $2.3 million during both the three months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, respectively, and $7.0 million and $7.3 million during the nine months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, respectively The amounts in 'Other' consist of various accrued expenses, of which no individual item accounted for more than 5% of the total balance as of September 30, 2015 or December 31, 2014 The amounts in 'Other' consist of various asset and inventory impairment charges prompted by the aforementioned restructuring plan, legal fees and facility maintenance fees. Includes expenses related to exiting stores and legal fees.
